{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01Q3pU5ihpSMGfrT2FwrMNDp","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01HwnEed2cxAWkoTTTDnaExr","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The request sent to the external API always includes the complete list of valid taxonomy labels.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure is a deterministic bug in request construction: missing labels from the payload. A unit test of the request builder alone won't catch the failure if the module doesn't call the builder correctly. A mock API client (Integration level) with call-argument verification can inspect the actual payload sent and confirm all labels are present. No real network needed—the bug manifests in local code logic.","test_description":"Mock the external API client. Call the classification module with a document. Capture the mock's call arguments and verify the request object includes all taxonomy labels in the expected field (e.g., request.labels or request.valid_options). Test edge cases: empty taxonomy (no labels sent) and single-label taxonomy.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.98,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When the API returns a label that is not in the taxonomy, the module returns \"unknown\" instead of forwarding the unexpected value to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure is: the module forwards an out-of-taxonomy label without validation. This is a deterministic response-handling bug. A mock API returning an invalid label (Integration level) will trigger the validation logic. No real network or LLM behavior needed—just verify the validation code path.","test_description":"Mock the external API to return a label not in the taxonomy (e.g., if taxonomy is {legal, technical, financial, other}, mock returns 'unknown_category'). Call the module with a valid document. Verify the module returns exactly the string \"unknown\", not the invalid label. Test both responses that are structurally valid but semantically invalid (e.g., a real string that's not in the list) and edge cases like null or empty string.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.99,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The classification result for the same document is the same across repeated calls.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The most likely implementation is caching: the module stores results locally to avoid repeated API calls. The failure would be: no caching, or broken caching logic (same input yielding different cached results). Testing this requires mocking the API and verifying it's called only once for two identical calls—Integration level suffices. However, uncertainty remains: if the requirement is that the real API is deterministic (unlikely for real LLMs), then Agentic level would be needed to detect non-determinism.","test_description":"Mock the external API. Call the module twice with the same document input string. Verify: (1) the returned classification result is identical both times (same label, same confidence if applicable), (2) the mock API was invoked exactly once, not twice (proving caching worked). Also test that calling with a different document triggers a new API call (cache is document-specific, not global).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Integration assumes caching is implemented. If the design relies on the real API being deterministic across calls (false for real LLMs), Agentic testing would be needed.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.25,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The number of tokens consumed for a typical document stays within the configured per-call budget.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure is: token consumption exceeds the budget, or the module doesn't enforce the limit. Token counting is typically deterministic—either provided by the API response or by a local tokenizer (e.g., tiktoken). A mock API that returns specific token counts in its response (Integration level) can test whether the module rejects or handles over-budget documents. No real network or actual tokenization needed to catch the logic bug.","test_description":"Mock the external API to include a token_count field in its response. Configure a low per-call budget (e.g., 100 tokens). Create test documents that would trigger: (1) under-budget (token_count=50), (2) over-budget (token_count=150). Verify the module either rejects the over-budget request (e.g., raises an error or returns a failure), or implements truncation to stay within budget. Log or return the actual token count consumed to verify it never exceeds the configured limit.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.75,"System":0.15,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When the API signals that the request rate is too high, the module waits and retries rather than returning an error to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure is: the module doesn't retry, or crashes/errors instead of waiting. The retry logic is deterministic code—either it's there or it isn't. A mock API that returns a rate-limit error (HTTP 429 or equivalent) on the first call and success on the second call (Integration level) will exercise the retry path. The mock can be stateful or use a call counter. No real network delays or actual rate limiting needed to catch the retry bug.","test_description":"Mock the external API with stateful behavior: first call returns a rate-limit error (e.g., HTTP 429 or {error: 'rate_limit_exceeded'}), second call returns a successful classification. Call the module once with a valid document. Verify: (1) the module does not return an error to the caller immediately, (2) the module makes a second call to the API (retry occurred), (3) the final result is the successful classification from the second call, not an error. Optionally verify a delay occurred between calls (check timing, or mock time.sleep and verify it was called).","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.75,"System":0.2,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0.05}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13305,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13305},"output_tokens":5,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f67b027f-834a-4585-8b0b-68588cba7105","uuid":"02e3b753-4134-415c-a01e-c8469fe28f84"}
